00:23.890 --> 00:29.050
And I did the senator a favor in the hope that he would do me one and use his influence to keep my brother home.

00:29.050 --> 00:31.890
Upon Dad's death, we can sell the land to the army.

00:31.900 --> 00:35.280
The land is worth over $30 million.

00:35.290 --> 00:38.600
I could use somebody like you on my communications staff.

00:40.250 --> 00:49.140
Noel, noel, noel, noel, noel, noel...

00:49.150 --> 00:51.760
He's been singing this song the whole car ride home.

00:51.770 --> 00:52.770
Great.

00:52.780 --> 00:55.980
Yeah, that's the face I made at first. Wait ten minutes.

00:55.990 --> 00:58.620
- Hey, how did you do with the lights?
- Hmmm, don't ask.

00:58.630 --> 01:00.290
Hey, Coop, do you know any other songs?

01:00.300 --> 01:01.430
- Yeah!
- Awesome.

01:01.440 --> 01:04.950
#Jingle bells, Batman smells, Robin laid an egg#

01:04.959 --> 01:08.460
#The batmobile lost its wheel, and the Joker got away, hey!#

01:08.460 --> 01:12.430
Awesome, dude. Rocks. Go practice upstairs.

01:14.080 --> 01:17.850
- Hey, babe. How are you?
- I'm good. You?

01:17.850 --> 01:21.520
- He's definitely your son.
- Yes, indeed he is.

01:24.400 --> 01:27.000
Hey, P., What's this?

01:27.010 --> 01:29.450
It's a Christmas tree ornament. We made 'em at school.

01:29.470 --> 01:32.480
It's a Jewish star. Hiroshi's has a buddha on it.

01:32.500 --> 01:35.280
Honey, did you remember to leave your new insulin kit at school?

01:35.290 --> 01:40.860
Yeah. Hey, Mom, today at lunch Mckenzie Brillstien told me that if your mother's Jewish, you're Jewish.

01:40.870 --> 01:45.010
- Is that true?
- Uh, yes. Yes, it is true.

01:45.020 --> 01:46.590
So why aren't we Jewish?

01:46.590 --> 01:50.410
Grandma's Jewish, which means you're Jewish, so I'm Jewish.

01:50.410 --> 01:52.790
So why don't we celebrate Hanukkah?

01:54.440 --> 01:56.220
That is a very good question, Paige.

01:56.230 --> 02:00.560
Um, I guess it's because Grandma never taught us about it.

02:00.570 --> 02:03.940
- But did she teach you about Christmas?
- No, not really.

02:03.950 --> 02:06.860
- But you had Christmas.
- Yeah. Yeah, every year.

02:06.860 --> 02:14.240
But why? If we're Jewish, we should be having Hanukkah like Mckenzie and Duncan and Moises.

02:15.490 --> 02:17.790
That is a very, very good question.

02:17.800 --> 02:22.560
First of all, your grandfather loved Christmas, and he wasn't Jewish, so that's just what we did.

02:22.560 --> 02:25.030
- So you just stopped being Jewish?
- Yes.

02:25.060 --> 02:27.250
No. No, no, no, no. You can't do that.

02:27.270 --> 02:31.350
But you can ethnically be Jewish, but at the same time...

02:31.360 --> 02:37.040
Santa's just so much fun as a symbolic holiday character who represents--

02:37.040 --> 02:43.650
-- is a real, real person-- not a symbol, but a magical man in a red suit who brings presents.

02:43.650 --> 02:47.690
But Hanukkah has a menorah and candles and eight days of presents.

02:47.700 --> 02:51.020
Honey, is that why you want to be Jewish? 'Cause the loot's better?

02:51.020 --> 02:55.230
You see? That's what religion does. It equates spirituality with materialism.

02:55.230 --> 02:57.940
I don't want to be Jewish. I thought we are Jewish.

02:57.960 --> 03:00.020
- We're secular humanists, honey.
- Secu-what?

03:00.030 --> 03:04.240
Okay, Mrs. Sartre, that's enough. I'm sending you the bills for the therapy.

03:04.250 --> 03:05.350
Hey, Tommy, what's up?

03:05.370 --> 03:09.030
The point is, Paige, religion can often lead to zealotry and war,

03:09.060 --> 03:10.990
exactly what's happening in the Middle East right now...

03:11.010 --> 03:13.010
Which is why I don't believe in organized religion.

03:13.020 --> 03:16.650
What I believe in is the A.C.L.U., and I've already signed all you kids up.

03:16.650 --> 03:18.890
Want to put some sprinkles on that one?

03:18.910 --> 03:20.540
I'm gonna do a snowflake.

03:21.360 --> 03:22.590
What did you expect?

03:22.600 --> 03:25.570
That Mom would be happy to retrain one generation of Walkers.

03:25.580 --> 03:29.000
Unlikely. I think she's glad Julia's pregnant to have another mind to warp.

03:29.010 --> 03:31.470
- This is serious.
- No, this is serious.

03:31.470 --> 03:35.030
Oh, god-- the look. I haven't seen it since the audit of '98.

03:35.050 --> 03:37.130
What is it, Saul? I thought we were out of the doghouse.

03:37.140 --> 03:39.570
I just got off the phone with your brother Kevin.

03:39.610 --> 03:42.140
He finished his review of the real estate documents.

03:42.150 --> 03:44.520
The army's still gonna buy the land for $30 mil, right?

03:44.520 --> 03:48.170
Oh, yeah, right, they will, as long as all the owners of the land sign off.

03:48.180 --> 03:51.500
- Okay.
- Holly Harper is one of the owners.

03:51.510 --> 03:54.870
It's right under the terms of this trust that your father set up.

03:54.880 --> 03:57.200
She owns a non-divisible third of the property.

03:57.200 --> 03:59.220
That's why he left her out of the will.

03:59.990 --> 04:02.810
- He'd already given her $10 million.
- Are you kidding?

04:02.820 --> 04:04.740
Anyway, she's coming in for a meeting at 5:30.

04:04.750 --> 04:07.680
I'm not giving that woman $10 million.

04:07.680 --> 04:10.510
Let's buy out her third before we sell to the army.

04:10.510 --> 04:13.100
Yeah, well, if we had that kind of cash, this wouldn't be a problem.

04:13.110 --> 04:17.360
No, they valued the land at $1.2 million. We can afford a third of that.

04:17.360 --> 04:19.970
- You mean, screw Holly?
- Worked for Dad.

04:26.840 --> 04:30.440
- I'm very sorry, but no.
- We're not asking for a discharge.

04:30.460 --> 04:34.140
We're just asking for an additional three months so Justin can get better.

04:34.150 --> 04:37.260
Mr. Walker, your brother has been ordered to report in two weeks.

04:37.270 --> 04:40.250
The army needs medics in Iraq, not in California.

04:40.280 --> 04:42.410
Justin has some serious medical issues.

04:42.430 --> 04:44.030
- He recently over--
- Overdosed, yes.

04:44.030 --> 04:45.750
It says so right here on your petition.

04:45.770 --> 04:50.260
Look, Mr. Walker, this is the military. Justin is not a civilian.

04:50.270 --> 04:54.330
He is a soldier, and we decide what to do with our own, not you. We're done here.

04:54.340 --> 04:58.480
- Yes, sir.
- I can assure you, we're not. Thank you.

04:58.490 --> 05:04.300
My advice, son, as a lawyer -- I wouldn't spend the next two weeks running around in circles with denied petitions.

05:04.310 --> 05:06.090
Thank you, sir. We won't.

05:08.070 --> 05:10.460
What did I tell you would happen?

05:10.470 --> 05:12.220
Oh, come on. Don't make me cheer you up.

05:12.230 --> 05:14.700
I don't need cheering up. I've fought the government before.

05:14.710 --> 05:18.820
What, in traffic court, Kevin? I mean, God, this is the United States army.

05:19.320 --> 05:21.560
Since when do you start listening to authority figures?

05:21.600 --> 05:25.050
Look, Justin, you don't have to hide the fact that you're scared of going back, okay?

05:25.070 --> 05:27.750
I'm not hiding anything, okay?

05:28.110 --> 05:31.160
I'm terrified, and I'm pretty sure that shows. And you know what?

05:31.190 --> 05:36.210
I don't have a lot of time left, but I have Christmas, I have surfing, I have you guys.

05:37.060 --> 05:39.380
- I have surfing.
- Yeah.

05:39.380 --> 05:42.160
Let's just enjoy the time I have left, all right?

05:42.170 --> 05:46.580
Five years ago, William bought a piece of desert land in Nevada.

05:46.610 --> 05:48.990
It was a bizarre investment, to say the least.

05:49.020 --> 05:52.330
Took our combined wit, a forensic accountant and a road trip,

05:52.350 --> 05:58.860
but we finally discovered this great trust that my father left for his wife and kids...and his mistress.

05:58.860 --> 06:03.200
I think the politically correct term is "the other woman".

06:03.200 --> 06:09.300
Under the terms of the trust, you're entitled to a one-third share of the property,

06:09.310 --> 06:12.940
and we're prepared to buy you outright today.

06:14.040 --> 06:16.950
- Buy me out?
- Yeah.

06:16.960 --> 06:23.540
You sign some papers, deposit the check, and bang,
you've got $400,000 to do your Christmas shopping.

06:24.070 --> 06:28.740
Well, I've, uh-- I've never been bought out before. This is exciting.

06:28.750 --> 06:32.020
Um, what is the total value of the land?

06:32.040 --> 06:38.320
It's been recently evaluated at $1.2 million. The, um, paperwork's attached there.

06:41.730 --> 06:46.250
But, uh, um-- I'm just a- a little confused about something, Saul.

06:46.260 --> 06:50.370
Yes, well, basically, the land is being held as a tenancy--

06:50.390 --> 06:55.060
No, what I'm confused about is why William would leave me out of his will completely

06:55.070 --> 07:00.820
and then make me a part-time owner of some useless piece of land in Nevada.

07:02.800 --> 07:07.510
Maybe he just wanted everyone he loved to end up in the same place.

07:08.120 --> 07:11.380
Well, you all seem a little anxious to want to buy me out.

07:11.390 --> 07:14.140
No, just to get on with our lives.

07:14.730 --> 07:17.030
I understand the feeling.

07:17.050 --> 07:21.260
I--I'm gonna think about this for a while, weigh my options.

07:21.290 --> 07:25.460
Thank you warmly, Sarah. It's been a pleasure, Tommy.

07:25.470 --> 07:28.820
Saul, you're...spectacular.

07:29.470 --> 07:32.930
- I'll be in touch.
- Yeah.

07:34.910 --> 07:36.760
That went well.

07:47.130 --> 07:50.370
Oh, I'm really gonna miss you if you get the ax, Kitty.

07:50.380 --> 07:52.590
Let's not get ahead of ourselves, okay? No one here's getting fired.

07:52.610 --> 07:54.870
Oh, sure. Except Kitty.

07:55.970 --> 07:57.940
You should be ashamed of yourself, you know that?

07:57.960 --> 08:02.230
You media-guzzling, apolitical whoremonger! You used to be one of us, Whit.

08:02.230 --> 08:04.550
All she did was show some damn integrity.

08:04.580 --> 08:06.880
But I guess that's got no place on cable TV, huh?

08:06.900 --> 08:11.440
Relax, Jack. No one's getting fired...yet.

08:12.840 --> 08:15.830
- Wanna take a walk?
- Sure.

08:22.910 --> 08:25.130
I'm gonna miss her so much, man.

08:26.700 --> 08:31.380
It's no surprise we've received a lot of response to your
attempted bribery of Senator McCallister last week...

08:31.430 --> 08:32.140
Yeah.

08:32.150 --> 08:35.809
Angry e-mails crashed our server, not to mention the N.B.S. stockholder reactions.

08:35.830 --> 08:39.299
I expected it. I have a signed letter of resignation ready to go.

08:39.309 --> 08:44.550
And normally, I would take it. But, then, your apology generated more than 200,000 viewings on youtube.

08:44.550 --> 08:47.060
- You're kidding.
- And then our ratings shot up 28%.

08:47.060 --> 08:51.420
Wow. So you... don't want me to resign?

08:51.450 --> 08:52.860
Hell no.

08:52.860 --> 08:55.220
In fact, I want to tailor the show to your strengths.

08:55.230 --> 08:56.280
I have strengths?

08:56.290 --> 09:01.390
Kitty, your range, your appeal-- you've got it all--multitudes, like Emily Dickinson.

09:01.390 --> 09:02.800
Oh, I think you mean Walt Whitman.

09:02.810 --> 09:08.120
See? You're smart--an American woman with vulnerability and guts.

09:08.140 --> 09:11.810
No more banter, no more stunts, just you alone up there every week.

09:11.820 --> 09:14.500
W-wait a minute. Did--did you just say "alone"?

09:14.510 --> 09:16.550
Warren's contract is up in a month.

09:16.560 --> 09:19.320
We're developing a Jon Stewart-like vehicle for Jack.

09:21.020 --> 09:23.730
Wow. Does Warren know any of this?

09:23.740 --> 09:27.660
No. I wanted to feel you out first.

09:30.950 --> 09:32.520
So?

